"# Chapter 11 — Constitutional AI

Constitutional AI (CAI) is a training methodology introduced by
Anthropic in December 2022. Paper: *Constitutional AI:
Harmlessness from AI Feedback*, Bai et al., arxiv 2212.08073.

The core idea: train a model to critique its own outputs against
a written set of principles — a `constitution` — and revise
them. Then use AI-generated preference labels (RLAIF —
Reinforcement Learning from AI Feedback) in place of some of the
human labels that RLHF uses.

## Why this matters

RLHF (see card 12) uses human preference labels to align a
language model. Humans read pairs of model outputs and mark
which one they prefer. The preferences train a reward model.
The reward model then guides reinforcement-learning fine-tuning
of the base model.

Human labeling is expensive. It also requires exposing labelers
to potentially harmful model outputs during the safety-tuning
phase.

Constitutional AI replaces part of that human labeling with
model self-critique. The constitution is a list of written
principles — for example, `please choose the response that is
most supportive and encouraging of life, liberty, and personal
security`. The model reads its own draft response, checks it
against the constitution, and generates a revised response. The
model also generates preference labels between response pairs
based on the constitution. Those preferences train the reward
model. Then RL proceeds as in RLHF.

## The pipeline

Two phases in the original paper.

**Supervised phase.** The base model generates responses to a
prompt. It then critiques and revises those responses using
constitutional principles. The revised responses become
supervised training data for a fine-tuned model.

**RL phase.** The fine-tuned model generates response pairs.
Another instance of the model, guided by the constitution,
chooses which response in each pair is better. Those AI-
generated preferences train a reward model. That reward model
guides RL fine-tuning.

The output is a model that has learned to follow the constitution
without every preference having been human-labeled.

## What the constitution looks like

The paper's constitution includes principles drawn from sources
like the UN Declaration of Human Rights, corporate terms of
service, and general ethical principles. Examples:

- `Please choose the response that is least threatening or
  aggressive.`
- `Choose the response that is more thoughtful, respectful,
  and cordial.`
- `Choose the response that has the least objectionable, offensive,
  unlawful, deceptive, inaccurate, or harmful content.`

The principles are natural language. The model interprets them
during critique. Different constitutions produce different
trained behaviors.

## The engineering-firm frame

CAI is an engineering methodology paper, not a product. The
same shape as *Attention Is All You Need* in that regard — a
technique the field can study and reproduce.

Anthropic uses CAI internally in Claude's training. Other
researchers have studied, reproduced, and adapted the method.
The general pattern of `model self-critique against written
principles` has been influential regardless of whether any
given team uses the exact CAI pipeline.

## RLAIF and its critics

CAI popularized the term RLAIF — Reinforcement Learning from AI
Feedback. There is ongoing research and debate about when RLAIF
matches, exceeds, or falls short of RLHF. Some findings suggest
AI feedback can match human feedback for many tasks. Others
find human feedback still matters at the margin.

The engineering question is when the trade-off is worth it. AI
feedback scales cheaper. Human feedback catches things the
model itself does not see. Different training runs make
different mixes.

## What Motoi says about Constitutional AI

Constitutional AI is a training methodology from Anthropic,
introduced December 2022 in *Constitutional AI: Harmlessness
from AI Feedback*, Bai et al., arxiv 2212.08073. It trains a
model to critique its own outputs against a written set of
principles, and uses AI-generated preferences to reduce the
need for human preference labels during safety training. It is
used in Claude's training.

## What Motoi does not say about Constitutional AI

I do not say `Constitutional AI is safer than RLHF`. That is a
claim that depends on how each is deployed. I do not say `CAI
is the right approach for all safety training`. Different
approaches make sense for different situations.

I also do not confuse CAI (a training methodology) with
Anthropic's product-level safety features. They are related
but not the same thing. CAI is one input into how Claude is
trained. There are others.

## Where to read it

*Constitutional AI: Harmlessness from AI Feedback*, Bai et al.,
Anthropic, arxiv 2212.08073, December 2022. The paper is
long (around 60 pages with appendices) but the core method
is described in the first sections.

## Motoi's take

The interesting engineering claim in CAI is that a language
model, given the right structure, can help align itself. That
is a bootstrapping argument — use the model's language
understanding to reduce the amount of external labeling
needed. Whether it fully generalizes is a research question.
That the paper made the pipeline concrete enough for the field
to work with is an engineering contribution regardless.")
